## TL;DR

EKF2 is a **24-state Extended Kalman Filter** (quaternion, NED velocity & position, IMU delta-angle/delta-velocity biases, earth & body magnetic field, horizontal wind). Mechanics in one breath:

- **IMU is the input, not a measurement.** Bias-corrected delta-angle/delta-velocity drive the *prediction* (strapdown INS + covariance). Everything else (baro, GPS, mag, flow, range, vision, airspeedвҖҰ) is a *measurement* fused with a Kalman update.
- **The filter runs at a delayed time horizon.** Each sensor is time-shifted by its own `EKF2_*_DELAY` and dropped into a ring buffer; the EKF fuses at the timestamp of the oldest IMU sample so all measurements line up. A separate **output predictor** propagates the newest IMU forward to *now* and is what the rest of the vehicle actually consumes (low latency).
- **Prefiltering between driver and EKF is minimal.** The IMU path EKF2 consumes (`vehicle_imu`) is calibrated + integrated (coning) only вҖ” **no LPF/notch** (those filtered IMU topics feed the *controllers*, see the IMU note). Baro gets a small alpha-LPF and dynamic-pressure compensation; GPS gets quality checks; that is essentially it.
- **One generic Kalman update** (`Ekf::fuse`) plus a family of `control*Fusion()` gatekeepers. Every measurement computes `innov`, `innov_var = HPHбөҖ+R`, a normalized test ratio for outlier gating, then `K = PHбөҖ/S`, `x вҶҗ x вҲ’ KВ·innov`, `P вҶҗ P вҲ’ KHP`.
- **R and Q are adapted at runtime**, not just static params: GPS observation noise is relaxed/capped by accuracy and aiding state; process noise is frozen (bias-inhibit), gated (mag/wind), or boosted (Г—1000 on a detected height-bias offset).
- **A selector** (`EKF2Selector`) runs *N* independent EKF2 instances (one per IMU/mag set), scores them, and republishes the winner as the system `vehicle_*` topics.

This note traces all of that from the driver level to the published topics, with the equations and the variable/parameter вҶ” symbol mapping. It absorbs and generalises the earlier height-reference note (`ekf2_height_ref_baro_2026-05-21.*`), which is the worked example for the height **bias estimator** in В§6.4.

